If the two roots of the quadratic $7x^2+3x+k$ are $\frac{-3\pm i\sqrt{299}}{14}$, what is $k$?
inference:
The roots of the quadratic $ax^2+bx+c$ are given by
$$x=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}.$$

So, in this case, we have
$$\frac{-3\pm i\sqrt{299}}{14}=\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{9-4(7)k}}{14}.$$

Solving for $k$, we get
$$\begin{split}-3\pm i\sqrt{299}&= \frac{-3\pm\sqrt{9-28k}}{14} \\\Rightarrow\qquad -3\pm i\sqrt{299}&= \frac{-3\pm\sqrt{-28k +9}}{14} \\\Rightarrow\qquad 299&=-28k+9 \\\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\boxed{\frac{290}{28}}.\end{split}$$

Final Answer: $\boxed{\frac{290}{28}}$. I hope it is correct.
